---
/**
 * Hub: earned income tax credit. Worked example by eitc(). Single/HOH exact;
 * page states MFJ is approximate.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import EITCCalculator from '../../components/calculators/EITCCalculator.tsx';
import { eitc } from '../../lib/credits';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';

const phaseIn = eitc(8000, 0, 1, 'single');
const plateau = eitc(22000, 0, 1, 'single');
const noKids = eitc(12000, 0, 0, 'single');
---

<Base
  title="Earned income credit calculator 2026 — EITC by income"
  description="Estimate your 2026 earned income tax credit. Phase-in, plateau and phase-out by number of children, the $12,200 investment-income limit, fully refundable."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Earned income credit calculator</h1>
    <p class="tagline">A refundable credit for working households — worth up to {formatMoney(8231)} with three children.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    The earned income tax credit (EITC) rewards work at lower incomes. It phases
    in as you earn, plateaus at a maximum, then phases out — so both too little
    and too much earned income shrink it. It is fully refundable: you receive it
    even if you owe no income tax. This estimates it from your earned income,
    family size and investment income.
  </p>

  <EITCCalculator client:load />

  <h2>Worked example — a single parent with one child</h2>
  <p>
    The credit is not flat. It grows with each dollar earned up to a plateau, then
    falls away. For one child, single, in 2026:
  </p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>Earned income</th><th>EITC</th><th>Where on the curve</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(8000)}</td><td>{formatMoney(phaseIn.credit)}</td><td>Phasing in (34% of earnings)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(22000)}</td><td>{formatMoney(plateau.credit)}</td><td>At the maximum</td></tr>
      <tr><td>{formatMoney(51593)}+</td><td>{formatMoney(0)}</td><td>Fully phased out</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>
    At {formatMoney(8000)} the credit is only {formatMoney(phaseIn.credit)} — 34% of
    what was earned — because it is still phasing in. Earning more here <em>increases</em>
    the credit, up to the {formatMoney(plateau.credit)} maximum. A childless worker
    earning {formatMoney(12000)} gets just {formatMoney(noKids.credit)}: the childless
    EITC is far smaller and phases out much sooner.
  </p>

  <h2>Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>How much is the EITC worth?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      For 2026 the maximum is {formatMoney(664)} with no children, {formatMoney(4427)}
      with one, {formatMoney(7316)} with two, and {formatMoney(8231)} with three or
      more. You only reach the maximum in the plateau range; below it the credit is
      a percentage of your earnings, and above it the credit falls.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Can investment income disqualify me?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Yes. If your investment income — interest, dividends, capital gains — exceeds
      {formatMoney(12200)} in 2026, you cannot claim the EITC at all, no matter how
      low your earned income. It is a hard cutoff, not a phase-out.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Is the EITC refundable?</h3>
    <p>
      Fully. Unlike a non-refundable credit that only cancels tax you owe, the EITC
      is paid to you even if your tax is zero. For many working families it is the
      largest single line on the refund.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Does marriage change the EITC?</h3>
    <p data-review="legal">
      Yes — married filing jointly raises the phase-out, so a married couple keeps
      the credit to a higher income than a single filer with the same children.
      For one child in 2026 the credit runs out at {formatMoney(51593)} single but
      {formatMoney(58863)} for a couple. This calculator uses the exact 2026
      figures for every filing status.
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="faq">
    <h3>Who counts as a qualifying child?</h3>
    <p>
      Broadly, your child, stepchild, foster child, sibling or their descendant,
      under 19 (or 24 if a full-time student, or any age if permanently disabled),
      who lived with you more than half the year. The IRS rules have detail the
      calculator does not — it uses only the count.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Related tools</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    <li><a href="/child-tax-credit-calculator/">Child tax credit calculator</a> — often claimed alongside the EITC</li>
    <li><a href="/child-care-tax-credit-calculator/">Child &amp; dependent care credit</a></li>
    <li><a href="/1099-tax-calculator/">1099 tax calculator</a> — self-employment counts as earned income</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="results-note">
    Estimate for the 2026 tax year. The IRS EITC Assistant is the authoritative
    eligibility check. Not tax advice.
  </p>
</Base>
